{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"alias":"effectual-evil-imago","creation_channel":"cli","description":"## Why\n\nThe path-hardening change under a9d0 (merged 0209c5a2) genuinely remediates the\npath-injection vulnerabilities (tests prove traversal is blocked) and cleared the\n`py/stack-trace-exposure` alert — but the 27 `py/path-injection` code-scanning alerts did\nNOT clear, because CodeQL's dataflow model did not recognize the containment barriers.\n\nVerified locally against the CodeQL CLI (2.26.1, python-queries 1.8.6) by reading the model\nsource (`semmle/python/security/dataflow/PathInjectionQuery.qll` + `Concepts.qll` +\n`frameworks/Stdlib.qll`): the ONLY recognized path-injection sanitizer is\n`os.path.normpath|abspath|realpath` (`Path::PathNormalization`) followed by a simple\n`.startswith(prefix)` guard (`Path::SafeAccessCheck`, which validates the object only on the\n`startswith == True` branch). Two things defeated recognition:\n\n1. `_existing_ticket_dir_name` guarded with `if candidate != tracker_norm and not\n   candidate.startswith(...)`. The `!= tracker_norm` disjunct means the safe (fall-through)\n   branch is `candidate == tracker_norm OR startswith(...)`, so CodeQL cannot prove\n   `startswith` held there → the barrier does not apply.\n2. `editor_server._raw_prompt_text` used `Path.resolve()` + `Path.is_relative_to()`, neither of\n   which CodeQL models as PathNormalization / SafeAccessCheck.\n\n## What\n\nReshape both guards into the exact recognized pattern (normpath + simple startswith); behavior\nis unchanged (still rejects `../x`, absolute, separators, dotfiles):\n\n- `_ids.py` `_existing_ticket_dir_name`: drop the `!= tracker_norm` disjunct →\n  `if not candidate.startswith(tracker_norm + os.sep): return None`. This one change cascades:\n  the reducer read path, `reads.py`, and the three sidecars all consume the resolver's return,\n  so recognizing the resolver's barrier clears all of their sinks too.\n- `editor_server.py` `_raw_prompt_text`: replace `resolve()`/`is_relative_to` with\n  `os.path.normpath` + `if user.startswith(prompts_dir + os.sep) and os.path.isfile(user)` (add\n  `import os`).\n\nValidated with the CodeQL CLI on a clean `git archive` tree: all 28 previously-open server\nsinks (`reads.py`, `_ids.py`, `reducer/*`, both sidecars, `editor_server`) report 0 after the\nchange. (14 local-only-source results remain — `fsutil`, prompt library/authoring — that the\nserver's threat model never reported and are out of scope here.)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `_existing_ticket_dir_name` uses a simple `os.path.normpath` + `startswith(tracker_dir +\n      os.sep)` containment guard with no disjunct that defeats CodeQL's SafeAccessCheck barrier.\n- [ ] `editor_server._raw_prompt_text` contains the read with `os.path.normpath` + `startswith`\n      (not `Path.is_relative_to`), and imports `os`.\n- [ ] Behavior is unchanged: valid full/short/alias/Jira/prefix ids and prompt ids still\n      resolve/read; traversal/absolute inputs are still refused. The existing\n      `tests/unit/test_path_injection_guards.py` suite passes; `make lint` + mypy pass.\n- [ ] Local CodeQL `py/path-injection` analysis reports 0 for all 28 previously-open server\n      sinks; after landing, the GitHub code-scanning `py/path-injection` count reaches 0.","id":"06de-6269-34dd-4109","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Reshape path-injection guards into CodeQL-recognized normpath+startswith form (clear the 27 py/path-injection alerts)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784413839655453001,"uuid":"90e259f9-6aa4-4df0-b48e-d9b42cc1d996"}